<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Michael Stein</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Written evidence submitted by Michael Stein</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Thank you for allowing this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> submission. I write in my capacity as a Professor of Law, as Executive Director of the Harvard Law School Project on Disability, and as one of the individuals who participated in the drafting of the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Person with D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">isabilities (CRPD). Since the CRPD went into operation I and my colleagues have worked to implement the treaty in some three dozen countries, mostly in the developing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">world, and as such we have collaborated with international governments, UN agencies, deve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lopment agencies, and always, disabled people’s organizations (DPOs). Our work has been recognized by numerous awards, for example, recently I received the inaugural Henry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Viscardi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Award for Global Disability Rights advocacy. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In sum, I write as a leading expert on disability and development. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">More than one billion people have a disability, many of whom are impoverished. Notably, disabled persons account for twenty percent of all individuals living below the global poverty line </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of one dollar a day. The phenomena of disability and poverty, moreover, are recursive and cumulative with one circumstance heightening the probability that the other will also occur. Inaccessible environments, cultural attitudes, lack of education and empl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oyment opportunities, as well as additional costs resulting from disability, each contribute to the elevated worldwide poverty rate among persons with disabilities. The reasons that the poor are at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sign</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">agency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cantly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> greater risk of disablement a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re equally apparent: malnutrition, inadequate medical care, limited </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and physically dangerous living and working conditions. The disability-poverty cycle leads initially to transitory poverty, and potentially to chronic and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">intergenerational pove</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rty. Ultimately, disability and poverty are interactive and cyclical, with one factor precipitating the other.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Given the dire status of the globe’s “largest minority,” development aid schemes logically should include people with disabilities, a fact noted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over a decade ago by then World</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Bank president James </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Wolfensohn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Nevertheless, individuals with disabilities remain among the most neglected of persons living in poverty. To illustrate, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">central aim of the United Nations Millennium Development Goals (MD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Gs) is to halve the world’s poverty by 2015. Nonetheless, the MDGs neither reference disability nor monitor their impact on disabled persons. International development assistance programs—whether focused on poverty alleviation, health care access, HIV and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">AIDS programming, employment opportunities, infrastructure construction, or dispensing humanitarian relief—have likewise historically excluded persons with disabilities from their purview. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Disability rights advocates have called for equal inclusion within</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the global development agenda repeatedly since the 1980s. In response, international development agencies have generated policy statements that rhetorically support disability in development but do not require its implementation, and by sponsoring a small</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> percentage of disability-spec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">projects. For instance, the United States Agency for International Development (USAID) issued path-breaking guidelines in 1997 indicating its commitment to disability-inclusive development, but has yet to enforce them. Al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ong similar lines, despite publishing comprehensive toolkits on how to achieve inclusive-development, barely more than six percent of World Bank projects contain a disability component. Hence, only a tiny fraction of the nearly one hundred billion dollars </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">spent annually on development and humanitarian schemes around the world reaches persons with disabilities. Eliding persons with disabilities from these programs sign</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ificantly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and deleteriously impacts their lives by increasing the equality gap relative to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">non-disabled citizens and distancing them further from mainstream society.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some of the harmful neglect towards persons with disabilities in development programming has been addressed as a legal matter by the CRPD which entered into force in May 2008. Notab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ly, Article 32(a) of the treaty requires all international assistance, including development aid to “be inclusive of and accessible to persons with disabilities.” Acknowledging this duty, States Parties—including the European Union which rat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ified</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the CRPD </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as a regional entity and is the world’s largest development donor—are evolving disability-inclusive aid initiatives. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are thus situated at a historical moment, one which can change the lives and future prospects of the global one billion persons with dis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">abilities through the simple and equitable act of including them equally in development schemes.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Achieving disability-inclusive development requires development agencies to undergo procedural, substantive, and ultimately institutional cultural changes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Procedurally, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evelopment agencies must enable meaningful disability civil society participation throughout their work, mainstream and twin-track disability programming across all sectors, and ensure accountability for inclusion. Substantively, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evelopment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> agencies need to adopt a rights-based in which people with disabilities are meaningfully included in all sponsored development schemes. To achieve these ends, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evelopment agencies will have to acculturate the notion that including persons with disabilitie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s is part and parcel of their international law obligations and not an element that can be added to programming when circumstances permit. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To achieve disability-inclusive development agencies must initiate a dramatic procedural sea change, one in which pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ople with disabilities are respected as agents of change and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enabled to participate fully in the development process, from planning and implementation, to monitoring.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Such an integrated method was utilized by the drafters of the CRPD, which became the firs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t UN human rights treaty to include members of the targeted identity group in its negotiations. The inclusion of persons with disabilities and DPOs in the CRPD’s development through this “participatory dynamic” reflected the aphorism of the treaty—“nothing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> about us without us.” States representatives, through interaction with persons with disabilities, were educated about their lived experiences and learned the priorities and needs ident</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ified</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by the group.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Collaboration was essential to the ultimate text, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hich mandates a similarly encompassing dynamic for the CRPD’s implementation. Notably, Article 4(3) requires states, as a general obligation, to “closely consult with and actively involve persons with disabilities, including children with disabilities, thr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ough their representative organizations” in law and policy development and “in other decision-making processes concerning issues relating to persons with disabilities.” Similarly, Article 32 on international cooperation requires that its inclusive developm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ent mandate by formulated and realized “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in partnership with relevant international and regional organizations and civil society, in particular organizations of persons with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.” More expansively, the Preamble’s aspirations are worth quoting at le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ngth:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 36pt 24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that the promotion of the full enjoyment by persons with disabilities of their human rights and fundamental freedoms and of full participation by persons with disabilities will result in their enhanced sense of belonging and in sign</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ificant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> advances i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n the human, social and economic development of society and the eradication of poverty.</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The process of making </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DEVELOPMENT AGENCY</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> development and humanitarian programming disability-inclusive can be achieved through ten procedural steps: </span></li></ol><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Locate DPOs with which to partner that have credibility with the local disability community. These DPOs preferably are managed by disabled people, and work towards ensuring representation by disability subgroups, including those highly marginalized like in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dividuals with intellectual disabilities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Conduct a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disability-spec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assessment through meetings with DPO representatives, disabled people, or via survey, to identify barriers to participation and ascertain priorities for future program development. Ai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">m for projects that respond to what the local population views as its top needs. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Designate a disability focal point to raise awareness of disability laws and policies, as well as the treatment of disabled people within a state’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">specific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">culture. In doing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> so, cooperate with local DPOs to ensure participation by the local disability community in sponsored work.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Employ people with disabilities in part or full time positions or as interns to enhance workplace diversity, improve relations with the local disabi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lity community, and increase program sensitivity to disability issues. Make certain that workplaces are accessible, and that accessible transportation is available. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Encourage and facilitate the participation of DPOs in planning, implementation, and evalua</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tion of programming, to ensure the best possible outcome as well as to provide the community with ownership of the projects. Meaningful participation must acknowledge the affect of culture and power relationships, and emphasis the equal value of all stakeh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">olders.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Make sure all programming facilities are accessible to and inclusive of disabled persons by including DPOs in inspections, planning, and evaluations of events. Sign language interpretation, provision of materials in alternative formats such as Brai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lle, large print, or on CD, and relocation to physically flat venues can provide equal access. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ensure inclusion of the needs of persons with disabilities in project selection and documentation. Proposed schemes can be reviewed by DPOs to assure that the e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">valuation criteria address the needs the disability community, remove barriers to their full inclusion, and prevent harmful practices.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Monitor implementation of disability-inclusive projects and activities in conjunction with local DPOs. In so doing, budge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ts can make provision for disability-inclusive practices, and if initially designed without input from disabled people, their participation can later identify barriers to inclusion.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Enable accountability toward the disability community by involving DPOs in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> monitoring and evaluating programs. These assessments ought to include disability-related indicators, and can be disaggregated by gender and disability subtype.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Foster collaboration and coordination on disability-related development project issues amongs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t local DPOs, international DPOs, local NGOs, development agents, and donors. Such networking can encourage sustainable interest in and support for current and future schemes. </span></li></ol><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Related to the process of including persons with disabilities as actors in all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aspects of development programming, is the process of including disability as a thematic issue across all sectors of development schemes through mainstreaming and twin-tracking. Mainstreaming a vulnerable population group means referencing and incorporatin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g issues relating to that identity category, here persons with disabilities, across all sectors of a development agency and throughout all its programming. Twin-tracking refers to spec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">targeting within development schemes of a vulnerable population gro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">up, in this case disabled people, by allocating resources and schemes spec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ifically </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">intended for their benefit, while also mainstreaming programming.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mainstreaming and targeting disability in development via a human rights approach is vital for developing i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nclusive societies and fulfilling disabled peoples’ human rights. Mainstreaming and targeted initiatives are needed because the issues faced by people with disabilities, including poverty, cut across sectors and necessitate cross-sector responses. In human</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> rights terms, the indivisibility of rights necessitates mainstreaming—ad hoc approaches leave gaps in policies through implementation, and cannot achieve full enjoyment of human rights and fundamental freedoms for the targeted group. To illustrate, a chil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d who uses a wheelchair requires clean water and sanitation, adequate food, a safe home, responsive health care, and accessible public transportation as prerequisites to gaining an education, all of which are in addition to an accessible school room and re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">asonable accommodations within the school. If a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> development agency </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as part of a public education project focuses only on physical access to a school but neglects other interrelated components, such as access to sign language interpretation, children with a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ural disabilities will be excluded from educational opportunity. Or, if a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">development agency </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in implementing an access to justice scheme duly considers the needs of only visually impaired persons to large print materials when sitting on a jury, but disrega</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rds parallel reasonable accommodations, for instance facilitating the involvement of those with intellectual disabilities, then that segment of the disability population will likewise be barred from equal participation. Hence, a comprehensive and coordinat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed response to people with disabilities is required within and across institutional operations and programs, and between stakeholders.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Experiences from gender-inclusion and environmental sensitivity efforts in development suggest that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evelopment agencies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">must promulgate strategic plans that are policy-intensive and time-bound if they wish to ensure comprehensive mainstreaming of a previously excluded group. The history of gender mainstreaming, although far from perfect, also indicates that mainstreaming ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n have a widespread impact on international development, and can alter the actions of international organizations.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">detailed plans are valuable for signaling the importance of an issue internally among staff, and establishing accountability in meeting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">designated obligations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Finally, mainstreaming disability to ensure greater equality for individuals with disabilities benefits not only disabled people but improves the quality of life of the whole community. Equality measures based on universal design pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inciples benefits not only people with disabilities but a broad spectrum of the community. A ramp allows the elderly avoid stairs and aids the movement of good. Moreover, mainstreaming and targeting allows people with disabilities to have greater access to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their communities and thereby increase those societies diversity. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Accountability for implementing development and humanitarian schemes is crucial for achieving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">development agency </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disability-inclusive programming, yet currently almost totally lacking with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in these institutions. As a consequence, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evelopment agencies issue strongly worded press releases or even policy statements, but then do not follow on these commitments.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The World Bank provides a clear example of how lack of accountability to a given issue results in its neglect. The Bank itself estimates that only 6.7% of its loans contain a disability component despite its expertise in creating and implementing schemes t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">argeted at persons with disabilities and in compiling data and disseminating technical assistance. Nor are prospects for change likely to occur in the absence of mechanisms geared at ensuring responsibility at the Bank for excluding individuals with disabi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lities from programming. Project proposals do not contain points to be awarded in their evaluations for including disabled persons. No safeguard policy exists, as it does in parallel for women, indigenous groups, and women. And currently the Bank’s interna</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l Inspection Panel does not recognize disability as a protected category under which complaints can be brought for Bank neglect. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stablishing effective accountability systems on disability is essential for ensuring that duties are fulfilled in a rights-ba</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sed approach and to strengthen good governance. Any alternative approach would lead to policies, however well-worded or well-intended, but without practical application. In this respect, the history of disability programming at USAID is highly illustrative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">USAID was one of the earliest bi-lateral donor agencies to adopt disability-spec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">guidelines.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The guidelines were precipitated by reports detailing the exclusionary nature of American foreign assistance, most prominently a 1996 report by the independe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nt National Council on Disability (NCD) that concluded “the United States does not have a comprehensive foreign policy on disability” and “neither the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">spirit nor the letter of U.S. disability rights laws is incorporated into the activities of the principal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> foreign policy agencies.” In response, USAID issued a non-binding guidance note in 1997 intended to avoid disability-based discrimination and promote inclusion in USAID programs and in host countries. Following subsequent and more detailed criticism by NC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">D and others,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">USAID made the 1997 guidelines part of USAID policy in 2004. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, because USAID’s policy is neither mandatory within the agency nor are there any internal safeguards for its implementation, USAID has continued to issue project solicitati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ons that often fail to incorporate the required disability policy provision, fail to reference individuals with disabilities as program participants or beneficiaries, and make no mention of guidance, budgeting, or reasonable accommodations that would enabl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e participation by disabled people. As a result of the absence of mechanisms to ensure accountability—despite repeated sincere and public representations by USAID’s chief Donald Steinberg that the agency would adopt and implement a fully inclusive approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to disability—USAID continues to violate its own internal policy by excluding persons with disabilities from its general development aid and humanitarian relief programming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is my earnest hope that the United Kingdom’s Department or International Deve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lopment will adopt and effectively implement disability-inclusive development practices and set a shining example for the world’s bi-lateral and multi-lateral development agencies.    </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 24pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>